Graminifoloside A (10) was purified as a white amorphous powder, with a molecular formula of C 53 H 66 O 25 based on the HR-ESI-MS: m/z 1101.3755 [M-H] - (calcd. for C 53 H 65 O 25 for 1101.3820). Comparison of the NMR data of 10 ( Table 4 ) with 7 showed similar signals, suggesting a close similarity in their structures. However, the major difference resides on the acid moiety which is an isobutylmalic acid in 10. In the 1 H NMR spectra, one methine and two methyl protons were observed at δH 1.77 (m, H-6), 0.76 (d, J = 6.6 Hz, H-7) and 0.83 (d, J = 6.6 Hz, H-8) which corresponds to the isobutylmalic acid group. This was further verified by HMBC correlations of H-7 and H-8 with C-5 and C-6 (see Fig. 4 ).. In addition, the absence of the benzylmalic signals in the 1H NMR spectra also validated this analogy. Moreover, the isobutylmalic acid moiety was established as a 2 R configuration based on the negative optical rotation which has been reported for previous derivatives (
;
,b;
;
;
). Thus, the structure of graminifoloside A was elucidated as 1-(ss- D-glucopyranosyloxybenzyl-4- trans -cinnamoyl-6-acetyl)-2-(ss- D-glucopyranosyl-2-ac etyl)-4-(ss- D-glucopyranosyloxybenzyl)-2 R -isobutylmalic acid and structurally determined as shown.

The isolated compounds were tested for their antioxidant activity against ABTS radical, DPPH radical scavenging and FRAP (
Table 5
). Antioxidant activity ranging from 543.71 to 1311.09 mmol Trolox equivalent/g sample for ABST radical, 370.67–545.03 mmol Trolox equivalent/g sample for DPPH and 103.14–1098.77 mmol Trolox equivalent/g sample for FRAP were observed for the isolated compounds (compounds 3–8).

In conclusion, eleven new compounds, including nine 2 
R
-benzylmalate derivatives designated as arundinosides I-IX (1–9) and two new 2 
R
-isobutylmalates derivatives designated as graminifolosides A-B (10–11) were purified from the undergrounds parts of 

Arundina graminifolia
D.Don Hochr.

This is the first report on the isobutylmalic acid derivatives in 

A. graminifolia
D.Don Hochr. It

is quite interesting to note that some orchids are able to produce this 
type
of glucosides based on different acids (benzylmalyl and isobutyl and tartaric acid) as the pivot (

; 

; 

; 

,b; 

; 

). The isolated compounds were tested for their antioxidant activity using DDPH, ABTS and FRAP assays. Compounds 3–8 showed antioxidant activity against DPPH (370.6–545 mmol Trolox equivalent/g sample), ABTS (543.7–1311.0 mmol Trolox equivalent/g sample) and FRAP (103.1–1098.7 mmol Trolox equivalent/g sample). Additionally, the compounds (3, 5, 6 and 8) showed cytocompatibility and cytoprotective effects in RAW macrophage cells.

